16 WHEREAS, the position of Georgia's Poet Laureate was established in 1925. As the state's
17 Poet Laureate, Rathburn is an ambassador for the literary arts in Georgia, championing the
18 rich legacy of Georgia's writers both past and present and cultivating new audiences. She also
19 judges the Poet Laureate's Prize, an annual state-wide high school contest. In this role,
20 Rathburn serves every corner of the state, voicing the value of reading, writing, literacy, and
21 storytelling in the lives of every Georgian; and
22 WHEREAS, Chelsea Rathburn is the author of three poetry collections, A Raft of Grief
23 (2013), The Shifting Line (2005), and Still Life with Mother and Knife (2019), as well as the
24 winner of the 2005 Richard Wilbur Award. Her poems have been widely published in the
25 nation's top journals, including Poetry, The Atlantic Monthly, the New Republic, The
26 Southern Review, New England Review, and Ploughshares, among others, while her prose
27 has been published in the nation's most esteemed journals, including Creative Nonfiction and
28 Ploughshares. In 2009, she received a fellowship from the National Endowment for the Arts;
29 and
30 WHEREAS, in 2021, Rathburn received a Poets Laureate Fellowship from the Academy of
31 American Poets to implement Georgia Poetry in the Parks, poetry trails featuring poems by
32 contemporary Georgia poets, in partnership with the Georgia Center for the Book and the
33 DeKalb Library Foundation; and
34 WHEREAS, it is abundantly fitting and proper that the outstanding accomplishments of this
35 remarkable, dedicated, and distinguished Georgian be appropriately recognized.
36 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
37 the members of this body recognize and celebrate Chelsea Rathburn as the Poet Laureate of
